{"id":"astro-ph/0406511","submitter":"Tadeusz Wibig","authors":"Tadeusz Wibig and Arnold W. Wolfendale","title":"No 'cut off' in the High Energy Cosmic Ray Energy Spectrum","comments":"7 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  It is often claimed that there should be a 'GZK cut-off\" in the flux of\nextragalactic cosmic rays, arising from interactions between the cosmic rays\nand the cosmic micro-wave background photons (e.g. 1 and 2). Some experiments\n(3 and 4) show particles of even higher energy than this value and this has led\nto claims for exotic processes (e.g. 5 and 6).\n  We contend that such claims are unnecessary - there is no predicted cut-off,\nrather a continuation of the injection spectrum at reduced intensity. We have\ncombined the world's data and shown that the prediction for a rather flat\ninjection spectrum (exponent: 1.9 - 2.2) in the case of universal particle\ninjection provides a reasonable fit to the data. Conventional forms for the\nparticle attenuation in the intergalactic medium (e.g. 7 and 8) have been\nassumed. Either protons or iron nuclei (or a mixture) will suffice.\n  Attention is drawn to another aspect, too, that of the losses on the\ninfra-red radiation which may be intense near to strong sources and for sources\nin galaxy clusters. The attendant magnetic fields near the sources leads to\nsignificantly long diffusion times through the strong infra-red fields. Two\n'case histories' are considered.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 23 Jun 2004 13:11:16 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 25 Jun 2004 07:00:05 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 26 Aug 2004 12:17:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
{"id":"astro-ph/0406512","submitter":"M. Didier Fraix-Burnet","authors":"Didier Fraix-Burnet (LAOG)","title":"First phylogenetic analyses of galaxy evolution","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Penetrating Bars through Masks of Cosmic Dust: The Hubble Tuning\n  Fork strikes a New Note (2004) 301-305","doi":"10.1007/978-1-4020-2862-5_27","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  The Hubble tuning fork diagram, based on morphology, has always been the\npreferred scheme for classification of galaxies and is still the only one\noriginally built from historical/evolutionary relationships. At the opposite,\nbiologists have long taken into account the parenthood links of living entities\nfor classification purposes. Assuming branching evolution of galaxies as a\n\"descent with modification\", we show that the concepts and tools of\nphylogenetic systematics widely used in biology can be heuristically transposed\nto the case of galaxies. This approach that we call \"astrocladistics\" has been\nfirst applied to Dwarf Galaxies of the Local Group and provides the first\nevolutionary galaxy tree. The cladogram is sufficiently solid to support the\nexistence of a hierarchical organization in the diversity of galaxies, making\nit possible to track ancestral types of galaxies. We also find that morphology\nis a summary of more fundamental properties. Astrocladistics applied to\ncosmology simulated galaxies can, unsurprisingly, reconstruct the correct\n\"genealogy\". It reveals evolutionary lineages, divergences from common\nancestors, character evolution behaviours and shows how mergers organize galaxy\ndiversity. Application to real normal galaxies is in progress. Astrocladistics\nopens a new way to analyse galaxy evolution and a path towards a new\nsystematics of galaxies.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 23 Jun 2004 15:35:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 3 Jan 2005 15:54:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-01-27"}
