{"id":"quant-ph/0406174","submitter":"Ingemar Bengtsson","authors":"Ingemar Bengtsson","title":"MUBs, polytopes, and finite geometries","comments":"15 pages; talk at the Vaxjo conference on probability and physics","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.1874558","report-no":"USITP 04-4","categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  A complete set of N+1 mutually unbiased bases (MUBs) exists in Hilbert spaces\nof dimension N = p^k, where p is a prime number. They mesh naturally with\nfinite affine planes of order N, that exist when N = p^k. The existence of MUBs\nfor other values of N is an open question, and the same is true for finite\naffine planes. I explore the question whether the existence of complete sets of\nMUBs is directly related to the existence of finite affine planes. Both\nquestions can be shown to be geometrical questions about a convex polytope, but\nnot in any obvious way the same question.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 23 Jun 2004 14:38:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 5 Jul 2004 10:49:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-10"}
